column1: What percentage of the vote will the Republican candidate win in the 2022 Texas gubernatorial election?
column5: ['50.0% or less and will not win the election', '50.0% or less but will win the election', 'More than 50.0% but less than 55.0%', '55.0% or more']
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
538 has Abbott's forecasted vote share right at 54.9%
Abbott won with 55.8% in 2018. That was a down year for the GOP nationally. All momentum is in the GOP's favor nationwide and O'Rourke is a weak candidate. Look for ~57% victory for Abbott.
Swapping into the 55+ category as momentum continues to swing toward the GOP in the final days
Average of two forecasts, the first of which includes a Laplace approach to polls, then adjusted a little to reflect 538's simulations.
Polling. Republicans seem to be on track for a 7-10% margin of victory. For whatever that’s worth these days.
(no change) I wonder if the Guv is campaigning against the student debt relief? ~40 million in the US may be eligible. I suspect many may be paying attention to the GOP led state suits.

(no change; no link ;-( ) A CNN Lite article earlier today (which has disappeared) discussed the White House surprise at how popular the student debt relief effort is with younger voters. They have parents and relatives who might care one way or another.
(no change) The student loan forgiveness will have ripple effects.
Texas is an interesting place. It's absolutely getting bluer, and Abbott might be liked but he is not loved. I can see him getting 53%-57% of the vote depending on how popular the Democrat runner is.
Shifting 10% from third to first bucket. @OEMichael post related to the Senate races.

Not since Bush in '94 -- the first election after the Democratic Party in Texas was broken -- has a Republican in a two-way race (2006 was a four-way race), won less than 55% of the vote in Texas' gubernatorial election. That said, the complexion of Texas has changed slightly in the last five years. Current polling shows Abbott winning but with a narrow percentage. Therefore, I'm calling it about equal chance Abbott wins with between 50-55 or 55+.
Polling. National Republican trend. Immigration issue.

(no change and probably a repeat) I do wonder if the Guv's immigration stunt(s) might hurt his election performance among LatinX voters. Just a small shift might up-end the TX "norms." —and whether one plans to vote for Beto or not, he is a serious, not scary candidate. YMMV
Think I went a little too heavy in the 55+ category, having misread the 538 popular vote projection as a current polling avg. Still a knife's edge around 55% though.
Averaging two of my forecasts.
(no change) I do wonder about the Guv's busing gambit. One can hate US immigration policy without approving stunts like that.
Given current polling, and allocating the undecideds roughly evenly, it seems probable that Abbott will get over 55%.

Republican stronghold but beto is showing increasing favour in polling

acknowledging my bias - my heart really wants Beto to win...that being said...abbott is still pretty consistently ahead in the polls - right now averaging between 3-7% lead but under 50% (right now 47%)....so leaning towards that being maintained but Beto has seen an uptick in polling data (from 39% to 43% over the last month)

Initial forecast, just to follow the comments.
Well, I live here and I vote, so I might as well do this forecast too. This is my initial, highly subjective forecast.

Happy to finally contribute a question on my namesake state2018, Abbot got 55.8% of the vote. Ted Cruz got 50.9% of the vote the same year, in what was tight race with Beto. That was a Dem wave year, so we might expect Abbot to do better this time. Trump got 52% in 2020, and we could expect Abbott to outperform that also. National environment is maybe 10 points more R than 2020 and 13 more than 2018.
